8","1317":"1317","Hill Morton.Warwickshire,England":"Hillmorton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Eastleigh, Essex, Eng.":"Eastleigh, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Hillmorton, Warwickshire, England":"Hillmorton, Warwickshire, England","Evesham, Worcestershire, England":"Evesham, Worcestershire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Astley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places in England called Astley (in Lancashire, Shropshire, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, and Yorkshire), from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The modern surname seems to be particularly associated with the one in Warwickshire. See also   Astle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Astle","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cheshire called Astle, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. There may also have been some confusion with <i>Asthall</i> and   Astley  . Or occasionally this may be a topographic name denoting residence on an ‘east hill’ (from Middle English <i>ast</i> + <i>hill</i> or <i>hull</i>), i.e. a hill to the east of a settlement.","English: perhaps also a habitational name from Astwell, Northamptonshire, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>wielle</i> ‘spring’.","English: habitational name from Asthall, Oxfordshire, from Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook’."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>,